m","Pancreas","Descending colon"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe embryological midgut extends from the second part of duodenum to the proximal two-thirds of transverse colon, including the \u003Cstrong\u003Ejejunum.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe foregut develops into the pharynx, oesophagus, \u003Cstrong\u003Estomach,\u003C/strong\u003E proximal duodenum, liver, gallbladder and \u003Cstrong\u003Epancreas.\u003C/strong\u003E The \u003Cstrong\u003Erectum\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Edescending colon\u003C/strong\u003E develop from the hindgut, along with the distal third of transverse colon.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The foregut gives rise to structures from the oropharynx to the second part of duodenum","The midgut extends from the second part of duodenum to the proximal two-thirds of the transverse colon","The hindgut develops into the distal third of transverse colon to the upper anal canal"],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95929"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15833"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95929","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/95929"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-14T12:09:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-14T12:09:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8524"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113910"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","l